\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 \fs0 4.3.1  Dysphoric arousal and social bonding\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 \fs0 The link between expectation violation and social bonding has been most explicitly made in the case of {\i negative} violations of expectations. Evidence from cognitive dissonance theory {Festinger1957} suggests that individuals experience visceral emotions of guilt due to a tension that arises between perceptions of individual performance (in a range of experimental tasks) and internalised group-level expectations that sanction and valorise certain normative behaviours over others{Kenworthy2011,Stone2001}. The tension between these cognitions relating to self and group can be resolved via two conceivable paths: 1) by adjusting behaviour in such a way that it aligns with the dominant, pre-established group-level representation, or 2) reject a belief in the group-level expectation in favour of an alternative hypothesis that supports the individual-level cognition. Theoretically, both paths are equally plausible, but it appears that, in ultra-social human ecologies, honouring a belief in group-level expectations is often the most viable. This is evidence by the evolved psychological power of internalisation and habituation of group-level norms {Chudek2011}, and the ways in which cultural practices have evolved to incentivise submission to group-level representations\emdash for example, either participating in rites of initiation or facing permanent exile or summary execution[cf.][18]{Whitehouse2014}\emdash over radical individual-level re-evaluation{Sosis2003}. Mechanisms of dissonance-activated pro-sociality and costly group commitment appear to be particularly relevant to the relationship between extreme ritual practices involving significant individual-level cost (fire walking, self-immolation, fasting, etc.) and social bonding{Sosis2003,Xygalatas2013,Bastian2014,Fischer2014,Whitehouse2014}.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 \fs0 It has been suggested that negative \ldblquote dysphoric arousal\rdblquote  is a more powerful and enduring emotional state than \ldblquote euphoric arousal,\rdblquote  and therefore a more effective mechanism for social bonding {Whitehouse1996,Whitehouse2004}. This assertion is verifiable in the anthropological record, in which dysphoric arousal is more predominantly exploited in extreme ritual practices {Atkinson2011,Whitehouse2014}. This explanation does not, however, account for the entirety of highly arousing cultural practices, nor does it preclude other cognitive and affective pathways to social bonding {Downey2014,Xygalatas2014,Fischer2014,Fischer2014a}. Culturally orchestrated experiences of euphoric arousal also abound, particularly in the case of modern sport, as the phenomenon of team click attests. Indeed, perhaps one explanation for the cultural evolutionary success of sport is the way in which it exploits {\i both} positive and negative emotional arousal\emdash the joy of victory and the pain of defeat responsible for activating distinct but interrelated pathways to social bonding and group commitment. }\par
