}\pard\plain\s5\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 \fs0 4.3.2  Alternative pathways to social bonding: euphoria of team click\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 \fs0 Exploring alternative pathways to social bonding, particularly pathways that involve positively valenced expectation violation, requires a more nuanced theoretical account of the social dimensions of euphoric arousal in cultural practices such as those that involve group exercise. Within the psychology of well-being, researchers have for some time recognised important distinctions between two states (and traits) of well-being, namely hedonia and eudaimonia {Ryff1989}. Whereas hedonia refers to more subjective and transient modes of positive affect, eudaimonia refers to a psychological motivation for deeper meaning or \ldblquote human flourishing,\rdblquote  and is identified in particular psychological (character) traits or \ldblquote virtues\rdblquote  {Baumeister2013}. Virtues represent stable individual- or group-level patterns of behaviour (or activity, as it is referred to in the Aristotelian tradition) of an objective moral quality {Fowers2015}. The virtue of \ldblquote resilience\rdblquote , for example, involves the activity of transforming pain or loss into sources of insight and deepened understanding of self and others {Ryff2015}; and \ldblquote loyalty\rdblquote  entails the activity of commitment and successful group membership {Fowers2015}. Eudaimonic well-being relates to behaviour in which personal growth, self-acceptance, purpose in life, autonomy, and positive relations with others can be achieved, and is a substantial predictor of life events, including many factors of health and well being {Ryff2004,Urry2004}.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 \fs0 These two psychological constructs of positive well-being\emdash hedonia and eudaimonia\emdash have recently been analysed at the neuro-cognitive level {Berridge2011}, with studies identifying neural correlates of eudaimonic well-being distinct from hedonia {Lewis2014}. It appears that hedonic processes generated by immediate sensory inputs function as the foundation for higherorder eudaimonic pleasures sensations, through processes of conditioning, association, and learning {Berridge2003}. In this way, eudaimonic and hedonic well-being are distinct but interrelated components of positive well-being, with eudaimonic well-being reliant on hedonic affect as its foundation {Berridge2011}. This evidence provides a much more nuanced picture of positive affect, and in particular demonstrates that positive emotional valence in active inference is contingent on action cohering with a complex assemblage of socially mediated expectations, and not simply hedonic reward from local sensory stimulation. Considered from this perspective, euphoric arousal experienced in cultural activities is inextricably social and therefore relevant to processes of social bonding. As anecdote and observations concerning team click suggests, the \ldblquote click\rdblquote  is not limited to the most proximal dimensions of joint action perception, but is rather contingent on the snug fit between a given joint action and a whole assemblage of hierarchically ordered expectations with implications for group membership and social cohesion. }\par
